	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>LDC proposal for improved sugar access </h1>

			
			<h4>
												14 September 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> The LDC sugar group presented a proposal to the European Commission on March 3 rd 2004 designed ‘to safeguard their current and future access to the European sugar market at remunerative prices within the context of renewal of both the GSP and the EU sugar regime’. The group believes that the proposal would help attract investment and build up a globally competitive sugar industry. It was presented against the background of the Commission’s ‘fall in price’ and ‘liberalisation’ options for sugar-sector reform, either of which would amount to ‘an almost complete negation of the benefits of the EBA initiative’, a development which would have ‘dangerous consequences for many LDC economies preparing for a new export market’.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> The LDC sugar group proposes that:</p>
<ul>

<li>the EU amend the current arrangements for sugar under the EBA initiative; </li>

<li>the EU defer the gradual liberalisation of import tariffs currently foreseen from 2006 to 2009 until 2016 to 2019; </li>

<li>the EU grant LDCs immediate additional access under a progressive second tariff quota covering all sugar products, and that the volume of this additional access be based on the assumption that the export capacity of the LDCs will increase by 15% annually starting, in 2004/05 at 466,033 tonnes, with this being capped at 1,425,606 tonnes from 2012/13 onwards; </li>

<li>this additional access should not impact on imports from traditional ACP suppliers to the EU; </li>

<li>anti-fraud measures should be established in order to ensure respect for rules of origin and to make sure that LDC sugar industries are the beneficiaries; </li>

<li>the EU commit itself to maintaining the value of preferential access at a remunerative level, since as pointed out in its November 19 th 2003 memorandum ‘substantially reduced prices in the EU market would be of little or no benefit to the development intention behind the EBA initiative’, and this would be an inevitable consequence of the implementation of the ‘fall in price’ or ‘liberalisation’ options for sugar-sector reform. </li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			

<ul>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.ldcsugar.org/" target="_self">Press release of the LDC sugar group ( March 3 rd 2004 ) </a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.sugartraders.co.uk/proposal0304.pdf" target="_self">LDC sugar group proposal ( March 3 rd 2004 )</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.sugartraders.co.uk/EU Sugar Reform Press Release 171103.doc" target="_self">LDC sugar group memorandum ( November 19 th 2003 )</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/rapid/start/cgi/guesten.ksh?p_action.gettxt=gt&amp;doc=SPEECH/04/116|0|RAPID&amp;lg=EN&amp;display" target="_self">Commissioner Fischler’s speaking notes (SPEECH/04/116-03/03/2004) </a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.sugartraders.co.uk/ebastats.htm" target="_self">Latest statistics of LDC sugar deliveries</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.ictsd.org/weekly/04-03-10/story4.htm" target="_self">ICTSD report (Vol. 8, No. 9, March 10 th 2004 )</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.tralac.org/scripts/content.php?id=2476" target="_self">Tralac report ( March 12 th 2004 ) </a> </li>

</ul>
		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> It should be noted that the November 19 th 2003 LDC sugar group memorandum expressed surprise that the EU rules out the fixed-quota option on the grounds that it would require ‘backtracking’ on EBA commitments in favour of two options which ‘renders the EBA initiative meaningless for sugar’. The memorandum noted that ‘the Commission seems to prefer maintaining free access for the LDCs into a market with a price that is too low for them to compete, over that of negotiating with the LDCs an orderly market that achieves a price that allows the LDCs to compete and create development’.</p><p> It is in this context that the LDC sugar group’s March 3 rd 2004 proposals need to be seen. However it should be borne in mind that the EC had its own internal reasons for abandoning the ‘fixed quota’ option. One of the anomalies of the current EU sugar regime is that it has encouraged sugar production in high-cost areas of the EU. The Commission’s fear is that any ‘fixed quota’ option would freeze in place these internal distortions and prevent the expansion of EU sugar production in low-cost areas, thereby undermining the development of a more cost-efficient EU sugar sector. It was these concerns rather than any fear of ‘backtracking’ on commitments to LDCs under the EBA which underpinned the Commission’s rejection of the ‘fixed quota’ approach to reform.</p>
		</div>
		
